summary: I’m quite new to he fandom (and this site) so someone had probably already said that, but
body:
I’m quite new to he fandom (and this site) so someone had probably already said that, but

Mirri Maz Duur never said Daenerys couldn’t have a child. She said (and I’m quoting from book 1) “When your womb quickens again, and you bear a living child. Then he will return, and not before”. This doesn’t mean that she couldn’t bear a living child, at all. It actually means that when she will, Drogo will come back to her. Because she will die in childbirth.

Talking about bittersweetness: Daenerys will meet the love of her life again, and Jon will be King of Westeros, raising their child alone. Or maybe he will die too, and he, Daenerys and Drogo will have a very awkward meeting in haven. That would be nice!

summary: Would passing off Jon as Benjen's bastard work? Send the baby home with Reed, get back to Winterfell and tell Benjen the truth...
question: Would passing off Jon as Benjen's bastard work? Send the baby home with Reed, get back to Winterfell and tell Benjen the truth and then make up a story where Ben had sex with a peasant girl who died and left her bastard baby alone?
answer:
Nope. Benjen was accounted for in Winterfell for the duration of the Rebellion, as far as we know. If he’d had a bastard child, it would have been local.

GRRM lined things up very carefully so that Ned taking Jon in as his own bastard is the best solution for Jon (and wrote Ned so that he would shoulder the dishonour by himself), to Catelyn’s detriment.
